Accompanying—Command required for a
Special Ability. (4.1.1)
Actions—Commands, Special Abilities,
Events, and decisions in the Winter Round.
(1.5.2, 3.0-6.0)
Adjacent—Regions next to each other for
actions or Events, Britannia being a special
case. (1.3.4)
Adulation—The bottom status of the Sen-
ate, best for Roman Faction. (6.5)
Aedui Confederation (Aedui)—A Gallic
Faction. (1.0, 1.5)
Agreement—Negotiation binding during a
Faction’s action. (1.5.2, 8.4.2)
Allied Tribe (Ally)—Static Forces piece, a
Tribe mobilized for war. (1.4)
Ambiorix—Named Belgic Leader. (1.4)
Ambush—Gallic and Germanic Special
Ability to improve prospects in Battle.
(4.3.3, 4.4.3, 4.5.3, 3.4.4)
Aquitania—Non-playable area. (1.4.2)
Arverni Confederation (Arverni)—A Gal-
lic Faction. (1.0, 1.5)
Attack/Attacker—Step/Faction in Battle
inflicting Losses on targeted Faction. (3.2.4,
3.3.4)
“Auto 1-4”—Event that Non-player Arverni
opt for without a roll. (8.7.2)
Auxilia—Roman mobile Forces piece with
aspects distinct from Legions and somewhat
similar to Gallic and Germanic Warbands.
(1.4)
Available—Forces in holding boxes, wait-
ing to be placed. (1.4.1)
Battle—Command that removes enemy
pieces. (3.2.4, 3.3.4, 3.4.4)
Belgic Tribes (Belgae)—A Gallic Faction.
(1.0, 1.5)
Belgica—A cluster of three Regions in
northern Gaul. (1.3)
Build—Roman Special Ability to place
Forts or Subdue Tribes. (4.2.1)
Besiege—Roman Special Ability to Subdue
Citadels. (4.2.2)
Britannia—A Region across the sea from
Gaul but adjacent to it for most purposes.
(1.3.4, 3.2.2, 4.2.2, 4.1.3)
Caesar—Named Roman Leader. (1.4)
Capabilities—Lasting Events that help or
hurt a Faction’s actions. (5.3)
Celtica—A cluster of Regions forming the
larger part of Gaul. (1.3)
Cisalpina—An area bordering Ubii, Se-
quani, and Provincia that becomes playable
as a Region only by Event. (1.3, 1.4.2, 3.2.1,
4.2.1, 4.4.1, 5.1.1)
Citadel—A static Forces piece, a Gallic-
allied City fortified for war. (1.4, 3.3.1)
City—Tribe space that can receive a Citadel.
(1.4.2)
Command—Core action that a Faction
takes with its Forces. (3.0)
Control—Possession of more pieces in a
Region or Region than all other Factions
combined. (1.6)
Control + Allies—Belgic victory marker.
(1.9, 7.2)
Control Value—Numeral in a Region show-
ing what Belgic Control there adds to Belgic
Victory. (1.3.1, 7.2)
Cost—Resources spent on an action. (3.1,
4.1, 6.3.3)
Cylinder—Token to mark a Faction’s Re-
sources or Eligibility. (1.8, 2.2)
Defend/Defender—Act as target/targeted
Faction in another Faction’s Battle. (3.2.4,
3.3.4)
Devastate—Arverni Special Ability to
starve enemies. (4.3.2)
Devastated (Devastation)—Marker on
a Region that has been acted upon by the
Arverni Devastate Special Ability to hinder
various actions there for the year. (3.2.1,
3.2.2, 3.3.1, 4.3.2, 6.6)
Dispersed—Marker placed on a Tribe by
Roman Seize to block Ally placement or
its Control for Belgic Victory. (1.4.2, 1.7,
3.2.3, 6.6, 7.2-.3)
Down—Senate shift toward Adulation.
(6.5.1)
Dual Use—Event with two alternative sets
of effects. (5.2)
Edge Track—Record of Resources and
some Victory. (1.8, 1.9)
Eligible—Faction able to execute Event or
Command: per Faction order, 1st and 2nd
Eligible. (2.3, 2.3.1)
Enemy—Of a different Faction involved in
an action such as Battle. (3.2.4)
Enlist— Belgic Special Ability to gain com-
mand of German Forces. (4.5.1)
Entreat—Arverni Special Ability to switch
Tribal, Warband, or Auxilia allegiance.
(4.3.1)
Event—Card with Faction order and text a
Faction may execute. (2.3, 5.0)
Execute—Implement Event or conduct
Command or Special Ability, for the latter,
in one or more Regions. (2.3)
Faction—Role: Romans, Arverni, Aedui,
Belgae, and (Non-player) Germans. (1.5)
Faction Order—Card symbols determining
Eligibility. (2.3.2)
Fallen—Removed Legions temporarily held
in a box. (1.4.1, 6.5.2, 6.6, 7.2-.3)
Final—Last Winter card. (2.4.1, 7.3)
Firm—Senate less prone to shifts. (6.5)
Flip—Switch a Warband, Auxilia, or marker
to its opposite side. (1.4.3)
Forage—The aspect of the Seize action that
gains Roman Resources. (3.2.3)
Forces—Warbands, Auxilia, Leaders, Le-
gions, Allied Tribes, Citadels, Forts (pieces,
not markers). (1.4)
Fort—Static Roman Forces piece represent-
ing fortifications in a Region. (1.4, 4.2.1)
Frost—Ban on March Commands during
last card before Winter. (2.3.8)
Free—Command or Special Ability via
Event that does not cost Resources or affect
Eligibility. (3.1.2, 4.1, 5.4)
Friendly—Of the same Faction or another
Faction that has agreed, such as to use of its
Control. (1.5.2)
Gallic (Gaul)—Arverni, Aedui, and Belgic
Factions. (1.0, 1.5)
Gathering—The back of a Dispersed
marker, still Dispersed but only until the
next Winter Round. (1.7, 6.6)
Germania—Regions east of Gaul. (1.3)
Germanic Tribes (German)—A 5th Fac-
tion, typically run by the game system. (1.5,
3.4, 6.2)
Group—Mobile pieces beginning together
in a Region and moving together. (3.2.2,
3.3.2, 6.3.3)
Harassment—Losses caused by Hidden
enemy Warbands during March or Seize.
(3.2.2, 3.2.3, 3.3.2)
Harvest—A Winter phase during which
Factions receive Resources. (6.4)
Hidden—Warband or Auxilia piece with
symbol side down, affecting certain actions
such as Scout, Retreat, Raid, and Ambush.
(1.4.3, 4.2.2, 3.2.4, 3.3.3, 4.3.3, for example)
Hide—Flip Revealed Warband or Auxilia
to Hidden. (1.4.3)
Home—Regions where Factions Recruit or
Rally more easily. (1.3.1, 3.2.1, 3.3.1, 3.4.1)
Ineligible—Faction skipped in Faction
order. (2.3.1-.2)
Instructions—Non-player Event execution
guidance. (8.2.1)
Intrigue—The middle status of the Senate,
neither most nor least favorable to the Ro-
man Faction. (6.5)
Leader—Roman, Arverni, and Belgic mo-
bile Forces pieces with numerous special
aspects. (1.4; for example 3.2.1, -.2, -.4;
3.3.1, -.4; 4.1.2)
Legion—Roman mobile Forces piece with
great hitting power and resilience. (1.4)
Legions—Track for Legions neither on the
map nor Fallen. (1.4.1, 6.5)
Limited Command—Command in one Re-
gion with no Special Ability. (2.3.5, 8.1.2)
Loss—Automatic or possible die-roll-based
removal of own piece from Battle or Harass-
ment. (3.2.2, 3.2.3, 3.2.4, 3.3.2, 3.3.4, 3.4.4)
March—Command to move and hide
Forces. (3.2.2, 3.3.2)
Mobile—Pieces that can move during
March, Retreat, Quarters, etc.: Leaders,
Legions, Auxilia, Warbands. (1.4, 3.2.2,
3.2.4, 3.3.2, 3.3.4, 6.3)
Next—Upcoming card. (2.2, 2.3.7)
No Control—Region not under any Fac-
tion’s Control (uncontrolled). (1.6)
“No [Faction]” Event—Event that that
Non-player Faction will decline. (8.1.1)
Non-Player—Gallic or Roman Faction run
by the game. (1.5.1, 8.0)
Off-Map (Legions)—Not in any Region;
Arverni victory marker. (1.9, 7.2)
Other Most Allies—Aedui victory marker.
(1.9, 7.2)
Overflow Box—Area to help manage cases
of overcrowding. (1.3.6)
Pass—Decline to execute an Event or Com-
mand when Eligible. (2.3.3)
Pawn—Token to designate Regions selected
for actions. (3.1.1)
Phase—Part of a Winter Round. (6.0)
Piece—Warband, Auxilia, Legion, Leader,
Allied Tribe (Ally), Fort, or Citadel (not
markers like Dispersed). (1.4)
Place—Put a piece from off the map into a
Region on the map. (1.4.1, 6.5)
Played—Pile with current card. (2.2)
Provincia—A Roman Home Region in the
southeast of Gaul. (1.3.1)
Quarters—Winter phase forcing pieces to
move or Resources to be paid. (6.3)
Raid—Gallic or Germanic Command to
take Resources. (3.3.3, 3.4.3)
Rally—Gallic or Germanic Command to
place pieces. (3.3.1, 3.4.1)
Rampage—Belgic Special Ability to
frighten enemies away. (4.5.2)
Recruit—Roman Command to place pieces.
(3.2.1)
Region—Map area. (1.3.1)
Remove—Take from map, for most Forces,
to Available; for Legions, to Fallen or the
Legions track. (1.4.1)
Replace—Place a piece in another’s stead.
(1.4.1, 4.3.1 for example)
Resources—Player Factions’ wherewithal
for Commands. (1.8)
Retreat—Move away from Battle or Ram-
page. (3.2.4, 3.3.4, 4.5.2)
Retreat Region—A Region to which Re-
treat from Battle or Rampage is allowed.
(3.2.4, 3.3.4, 4.5.2)
Reveal—Flip Hidden Warband or Auxilia
to Revealed. (1.4.3)
Revealed—Warband or Auxilia symbol up;
other Forces always. (1.4.3)
Rhenus—River bordering Germania slow-
ing Roman March (1.3.5, 3.2.2)
River Tolls—Added Aedui revenue during
Harvest. (6.4.3)
Roman Republic (Romans)—A non-Gallic
player Faction. (1.0, 1.5)
Round—Series of phases comprising
Winter. (6.0)
Scout—Roman Special Ability to move
Auxilia and Reveal Warbands. (4.2.2)
Scouted—Marker and Warband status
caused by Scout Command. (4.2.2)
Seize—Roman Command to garner Re-
sources, Disperse Tribes. (3.2.3)
Select—Choose an action’s locations or
targets. (3.1, 4.1, 5.1)
Senate (Roman Senate)—Marker showing
Rome’s political posture toward Caesar.
(1.4.1, 6.5)
Sequence of Play—Order of activities for
either an Event card or Winter. (2.0, 6.0)
Shaded—2nd choice of Dual-Use Event,
often anti-Roman. (5.2)
Shift—Move Senate up (toward Uproar) or
down (toward Adulation). (6.5)
Special Ability—Faction-specific action
accompanying a Command. (4.0)
Spring—Winter Phase at to ready for the
coming year and next card. (6.6)
Stacking—Limits on pieces that can occupy
a space. (1.4.2)
Subdue—Remove Ally or Citadel from a
Tribe circle. (1.3.2, 1.7)
Subdued—Tribe that is neither Allied nor
Dispersed. (1.7)
Subdued + Dispersed + Allies—Roman
victory marker. (1.9, 7.2)
Suborn—Aedui Special Ability. (4.4.2)
Successor—Leader that replaces a removed
named Leader. (1.3, 6.6)
Sudden Frost—Alternative Frost rule op-
tion. (2.3.8)
Supply Line (Supply)—Chain of Regions
affecting Recruit, Build, Trade, and Quar-
ters. (3.2.1, 4.2.1, 4.4.1, 6.3.3)
Target—Enemy Faction or piece that is the
object of an action. (3.1, 4.1)
Trade—Aedui Special Ability that garners
Resources. (4.4.1)
Transfer—Move Resources among Fac-
tions. (1.5.2, 1.8)
Tribe—Named space that can hold an Ally
disc. (1.3.2, 1.7)
Unshaded—1st choice of Dual-Use Event,
often pro-Roman. (5.2)
Up—Senate shift toward Uproar. (6.5.1)
Uproar—The top status of the Senate, ad-
verse to the Roman Faction. (6.5)
Vercingetorix—Named Arverni Leader.
(1.4)
Victory Margin—Calculation of a Faction’s
closeness to its victory condition. (7.3)
Voluntary Removal—Ability of a Faction
to remove or replace its own pieces. (1.4.1)
Warband—Gallic and Germanic mobile
Forces piece. (1.4)
Winter—Cards triggering Rounds that
include victory checks and several other
periodic functions. (2.4, 6.0)
Within one Region—In that Region and/or
adjacent Regions. (4.1.2, etc.)
Year—Event card series leading up to a
Winter Round. (2.4)
